===Gardner Earl Memorial Chapel and Crematorium===
[[File:OakwoodChapel.jpg|thumb|Gardner Earl Memorial Chapel and Crematorium|alt=Dark stone-faced building with tall bell tower at left. Arches connect to the main receiving rooms and chapel; roof is a slate blue color.]]
The most significant building on the property is the Gardner Earl Memorial Chapel and Crematorium, a [[Richardsonian Romanesque]] structure built between 1887 and 1889, which sits near the edge of the escarpment about {{convert|300|ft|m}} above the Hudson. The building was financed by William S. Earl, a successful Troy manufacturer, as a memorial to his son who became ill and died on a trip to [[Europe]] in March 1887.<ref name=bliss398>[http://books.google.com/books?id=HL_64rinz-EC&dq=earl%20crematorium&lr=&as_brr=1&pg=PA398#v=onepage&q=&f=false Bliss] (1897), p. 398</ref> The deceased son was an early promoter of [[cremation]]<ref name=bliss398/> and was himself cremated in [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]].<ref name=cobb93>[http://books.google.com/books?id=b2kPAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22oakwood%20cemetery%22%20troy&lr=&as_brr=1&pg=PA93#v=onepage&q=&f=false Cobb] (1901), p. 93</ref> 

The building consists of a {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} [[bell tower]] with an {{convert|18|ft|m|adj=on}} square base on the south side, connected by a triple-arched [[loggia]] to a [[chapel]] and [[crematorium]] on the north side. The floor plan of the entire building measures {{convert|136|by|70|ft|m}}. The exterior is covered by a pink-tinted [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]] [[granite]] and the [[foundation (engineering)|foundation]] sits completely on [[bedrock]].<ref name=cobb94>[http://books.google.com/books?id=b2kPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q=&f=false Cobb] (1901), p. 94</ref>

The interior is noted for its sumptuous and intricate design. The original furnace room was transformed into an elaborately designed reception room in 1889, the furnaces having been moved into a separate room. This features significant use of marble, from [[Siena]], [[Japan]], and [[Africa]], on its walls, floors, and even molding.<ref name=cobb96>[http://books.google.com/books?id=b2kPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA96#v=onepage&q=&f=false Cobb] (1901), p. 96</ref> ''The Troy Daily Times'' stated on November 7, 1889, that, "the chapel is a model of architectural and mechanical skill,"<ref name=cobb94/> and that the chapel's reception room "is certainly the equal, and possibly in respect to artistic detail and elaborateness of execution, the superior of any church interior in the land."<ref name=cobb9495>[http://books.google.com/books?id=b2kPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q=&f=false Cobb] (1901), pp. 94<U+2013>95</ref>

The interior of the chapel is marked by quartered oak ceilings, bluestone floors, and five original [[Louis Comfort Tiffany|Tiffany]] [[stained glass window]]s. The [[chancel]] contains an [[onyx]] [[altar]] and [[mosaic]] floor comprised of more than twenty colors of marble.<ref name =cobb9495/>

===Warren Family Mortuary Chapel===
[[File:Warren Chapel Oakwood 2.JPG|thumb|Warren Family Mortuary Chapel|alt=Light colored, stone-faced facade with steep gabled roof and Gothic door blocked by iron gate. To the right is a tall tower topped by a cross.]]
The Warren Family Mortuary Chapel is a stone chapel built on a knoll near the center of the cemetery. It was designed by [[Henry Dudley]] of [[New York City]] and built in 1860 in the [[English Gothic architecture|English country Gothic style]], complete with a [[nave]] and [[transcept]] floor plan.<ref name=nrhp6>Harrison (1984), p. 6</ref> A tower was added in 1883, with great care placed on finding building material that matched the earlier structure. The Chapel contains stained glass windows designed by artist [[Robert Walter Weir]] above the altar.<ref name=nrhp7>Harrison (1984), p. 7</ref> Former member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] [[Joseph Mabbett Warren]] (1813<U+2013>1896) is interred in the chapel.<ref name=joewarren/>

===Vanderheyden Bell===
[[File:Earl Chapel 4.JPG|thumb|The Vanderheyden Bell seen in front of the Earl Crematorium|alt=Grassy knoll with four wood posts holding up a green copper bell to the left. Crematorium in background, with bright sun rendering much of the image shadowed.]]
The Vanderheyden Bell, a memorial itself, is located northeast of the Earl Crematorium. It is a bronze, cast bell weighing more than  {{convert|3000|lb|kg}}. Its original home was under a log shelter on the premises. At some point, it was placed into storage. In 1971 it was resurrected and hung among four [[Sequoia|redwood]] posts, becoming an additional "tower" on the property.<ref name=nrhp8>Harrison (1984), p. 8</ref>

===Mausolea===
Oakwood is home to 24 mausolea and [[Burial vault (tomb)|burial vaults]] exhibiting a wide range of architectural styles including [[Greek Revival]], [[Egyptian Revival]], [[Roman Revival]], [[Gothic Revival]], [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Romanesque]], and [[Palladian]].<ref name=nrhp4/> These structures are scattered throughout the grounds, some clustered, some not. They house the remains of some of Troy's wealthier and more important historical figures.

The [[:File:Oakwood Mausoleum.JPG|Cannon Mausoleum]] exemplifies a Roman temple, complete with a cross-shaped floor plan and a domed roof. The [[:File:Strope Mausoleum Oakwood.JPG|Strope Mausoleum]] is a simplified Greek Revival structure, with a bronze door in the [[Art Nouveau]] style displaying an [[angel]] surrounded by lilies. The [[:File:Tracy Mausoleum 3.JPG|Tracy Mausoleum]], incorporating the most eclectic mix of design influences on the property, has a rock-faced stone exterior covered with foliate carvings. It displays a combination of Romanesque, [[Moorish architecture|Moorish]], and [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] elements, and is topped with a "[[beehive]]" roof&mdash;one of its more recognizable design features. The [[:File:Tibbits Mausoleum Oakwood.JPG|Tibbits Mausoleum]], [[:File:Oakwood 1.JPG|Vail Vault]], and [[:File:Gale Mausoleum Oakwood.JPG|Gale Mausoluem]] are all done in the Gothic Revival style. The [[:File:Kemp Mausoleum Oakwood.JPG|Kemp Mausoleum]] is the Palladian representative on site and the [[:File:Paine Mausoleum Oakwood 1.jpg|Paine Mausoleum]] is another eclectic design, octagonal in shape, and flanked by benches.<ref name=nrhp7/><ref name=nrhp15>Harrison (1984), p. 15</ref><ref name=nrhp16>Harrison (1984), p. 16</ref>

The [[:File:Russell Sage Mausoleum 3.JPG|Sage Mausoleum]], built of [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]] granite,<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=8eoJAAAAIAAJ&dq=sage%20mausoleum%20oakwood&as_brr=1&pg=PA73#v=onepage&q=&f=false Richardson] (1917), p. 73</ref> exhibits obvious [[Greek architecture|Greek]] influences and is intentionally not marked. [[Russell Sage]], the wealthy financier and member of the United States House of Representatives from Troy, is interred alone; his second wife Margaret decided to be buried with her parents in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]].  To the left of the memorial is a bench that contains a relief of [[Medusa]] on the center of the back, complete with snakes as hair.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oakwood Cemetery: History |publisher=Troy Cemetery Association |accessdate=2009-10-09 |url=http://www.oakwoodcemetery.org/history.php#graves}}</ref>
