===The Panorama===
[[File:Oakwood Panorama Sign.JPG|right|150px|alt=A long, wide photo rests upon three support columns on the face of a steep hill. A hilly landscape and river, with city housing, can be seen in the background.]]
''The Panorama'' is an {{convert|84|in|cm|adj=on}} [[panorama|panoramic photograph]] created by local photographer Tom Wall and set in acrylic on a steel stand in the cemetery's northwestern section. It sits at the edge of a bluff directly overlooking the grounds of Lansingburgh High School and Knickerbacker Middle School. The photograph spans a {{convert|100|mi|km|adj=on}} view and contains labels and notes<U+2014>referred to by the Troy Cemetery Association as "cliff notes"<U+2014>about the history of objects shown in the photograph.<ref>{{cite web |title=2007 Newsletter |publisher=Troy Cemetery Association |url=http://www.oakwoodcemetery.org/images/07news4.pdf |page=4 |format=pdf |accessdate=2009-10-10}}</ref> From this point, one can view [[Albany, New York|Albany]] and the [[Empire State Plaza]] (most notably the [[Corning Tower]] and [[Alfred E. Smith Building]]), the [[Helderberg Escarpment]], South Troy, [[Central Troy Historic District|downtown Troy]], Lansingburgh, [[Watervliet, New York|Watervliet]], [[Green Island, New York|Green Island]], [[Cohoes, New York|Cohoes]], the [[Cohoes Falls]], [[Waterford, New York|Waterford]], the Hudson River, the confluence of the Mohawk and Hudson Rivers, and the eastern terminal of the [[Erie Canal]]. The Troy Cemetery Association claims that the view offers the "most concentrated and complete overview of American history anywhere in America".<ref name=history>{{cite web |title=Oakwood Cemetery: History |publisher=Troy Cemetery Association |url=http://www.oakwoodcemetery.org/history.php |accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref> It shows evidence of paleolithic rocks, [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]], the [[Dutch Empire|Dutch]], the [[British Empire|British]], the [[French and Indian Wars]], the [[American Revolution]], the [[Industrial Revolution#United States|Industrial Revolution]], and the "Way West" movement resulting in the creation of the Erie Canal and [[Champlain Canal]].<ref name=history/>
[[File:TroyPanoOakwood.jpg|thumb|center|800px|Recreation of Wall's photo ''The Panorama'' showing the view from prospect overlooking Lansingburgh|alt=A wide panoramic shot begins and ends in bushes but is graced by two and three story city houses throughout most of the image. Front and center are three large schools featuring a track, tennis courts, and a football field. Behind the houses is a river flowing right to left.]]

==Notable interments==
[[File:Uncle Sam Grave 5.JPG|thumb|Gravestone of [[Samuel Wilson]], progenitor of [[Uncle Sam]]|alt=Close up of a grave stone (on the right) flanked by a red, white, and blue flower wreath (with ribbon and flag) on the left. Among other things, the stone reads "In Loving Memory of Uncle Sam"]]
There are a number of historically prominent figures buried at Oakwood. At least fourteen members of the United States House of Representatives (all from New York) are buried there, including [[E. Harold Cluett]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Cluett, Ernest Harold, (1874 - 1954) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C000535}}</ref> [[John Paine Cushman]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Cushman, John Paine, (1784 - 1848) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C001019}}</ref> [[John Dean Dickinson]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Dickinson, John Dean, (1767 - 1841) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000322}}</ref> [[William Henry Draper (Congressman)|William Henry Draper]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Draper, William Henry, (1841 - 1921) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=D000489}}</ref> [[Edward Whitford Greenman]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Greenman, Edward Whitford, (1840 - 1908) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=G000433}}</ref> [[Job Pierson]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Pierson, Job, (1791 - 1860) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000343}}</ref> [[Russell Sage]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Sage, Russell, (1816 - 1906) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000013}}</ref> [[Dean Park Taylor]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Taylor, Dean Park, (1902 - 1977) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000070}}</ref> [[John Richardson Thurman]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Thurman, John Richardson, (1814 - 1854) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000252}}</ref> [[George Tibbits]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Tibbits, George, (1763 - 1849) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000262}}</ref> [[Martin Ingham Townsend]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Townsend, Martin Ingham, (1810 - 1903) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000336}}</ref> [[Henry Vail]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Vail, Henry, (1782 - 1853) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=V000002}}</ref> [[Joseph Mabbett Warren]] (also the mayor of Troy),<ref name=joewarren>{{cite web |title=Warren, Joseph Mabbett, (1813 - 1896) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000165}}</ref> and [[Eliphalet Wickes]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wicks, Eliphalet, (1769 - 1850) |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=United States Congress |accessdate=2009-10-09 |date= |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000440}}</ref> The cemetery also has its fair share of military men, such as J. B. Carr, a general during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]];<ref name=troy100>[http://books.google.com/books?id=ouZPAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22russell%20sage%22%20oakwood&as_brr=1&pg=PA100#v=onepage&q=&f=false Encyclopedia Americana] (1920), p. 100</ref> [[John Augustus Griswold]], a promoter of ironclad ships and manufacturer of iron panels for the [[USS Monitor|USS ''Monitor'']];<ref name=nrhp13/> [[George Henry Thomas]], a general during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], nicknamed the "Rock of [[Battle of Chickamauga|Chickamauga]]";<ref name=troy100/> and [[John E. Wool]], commander-in-chief of the American forces during the [[Mexican-American War]].<ref name=troy100/>

As previously mentioned, the founders of Troy and [[Lansingburgh, New York|Lansingburgh]], Jacob D. Vanderheyden and Abraham Jacob Lansing respectively, were both reentered at Oakwood, having been moved there from downtown in 1869.<ref name=history/> Some of education's finest teachers are also buried there, including [[Amos Eaton]], a well-known botanist and geologist and founder of [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]];<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=2e4WAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA232#v=onepage&q=&f=false Ballard] (1897), p. 232</ref> Mary Warren, founder of America's first educational institution for "problem children";<ref name=nrhp13>Harrison (1984), p. 13</ref> and [[Emma Willard]], pioneer of women's education and founder of the Troy Female Seminary, which was later renamed [[Emma Willard School]] in her honor.<ref name=nrhp13/> Finally, Oakwood is also the final resting place of [[Samuel Wilson]], the progentor of America's national symbol, [[Uncle Sam]].<ref name=nrhp12>Harrison (1984), p. 12</ref>

